specs.title: Source
specs.html: British Retail Consortium (latest release)

specs.title: Measures
specs.html: Change in the price of goods purchased at BRC-member retail stores;

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: 'Actual' greater than 'Forecast' is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Released monthly, usually the last Wednesday of the current month;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Oct 29, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: Leads the government-released consumer inflation data by about 10 days, but has a narrower scope as it only includes goods purchased from retailers who belong to the BRC.  This data is usually released 1 day before the Bank of England interest rate decision. Full reports are only available to BRC subscribers;

specs.title: Acro Expand
specs.html: British Retail Consortium (BRC);

specs.title: Source
specs.html: Statistics Bureau (latest release)

specs.title: Measures
specs.html: Percentage of the total work force that is unemployed and actively seeking employment during the previous month;

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: 'Actual' less than 'Forecast' is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Released monthly, about 30 days after the month ends;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Oct 29, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: Tends to have a muted impact relative to employment data from other countries because the Japanese economy is more reliant on the industrial sector than personal spending;

specs.title: Also Called
specs.html: Jobless Rate;

specs.title: Source
specs.html: Bank of Japan (latest release)

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: More hawkish than expected is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Scheduled 8 times per year, about 10 days after the Monetary Policy Statement is released;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Nov 11, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: This report includes the BOJ's projection for inflation and economic growth. Source first released in Feb 2016;

specs.title:
Why Traders
Care
specs.html: It's the primary tool the BOJ uses to communicate their economic and monetary projections to investors;

specs.title: Acro Expand
specs.html: Bank of Japan (BOJ);

specs.title: Source
specs.html: Bank of Japan (latest release)

specs.title: Measures
specs.html: Level of a diffusion index based on surveyed large manufacturers;

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: 'Actual' greater than 'Forecast' is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Released quarterly, around the end of current quarter;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Dec 13, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: Above 0.0 indicates improving conditions, below indicates worsening conditions.  Manufacturing plays a critical role in the Japanese economy, and this survey is considered the best gauge of the industry's health due to it's large sample size and respected source. Source changed series calculation formula as of April 2004;

specs.title:
Why Traders
Care
specs.html: It's a leading indicator of economic health - businesses react quickly to market conditions, and changes in their sentiment can be an early signal of future economic activity such as spending, hiring, and investment;

specs.title: Derived Via
specs.html: Survey of about 950 large manufacturers which asks respondents to rate the relative level of general business conditions;

specs.title: Also Called
specs.html: Tankan Large Manufacturers Index;

specs.title: Source
specs.html: Bank of Japan (latest release)

specs.title: Measures
specs.html: Level of a diffusion index based on surveyed large businesses, excluding the manufacturing industry;

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: 'Actual' greater than 'Forecast' is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Released quarterly, around the end of current quarter;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Dec 13, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: Above 0.0 indicates improving conditions, below indicates worsening conditions. Source changed series calculation formula as of April 2004;

specs.title:

specs.html: It's a leading indicator of economic health - businesses react quickly to market conditions, and changes in their sentiment can be an early signal of future economic activity such as spending, hiring, and investment;

specs.title: Derived Via

specs.title: Also Called
specs.html: Tankan Large Non-Manufacturing Index;

specs.title: Source
specs.html: S&P Global (latest release)

specs.title: Measures
specs.html: Level of a diffusion index based on surveyed purchasing managers in the manufacturing industry;

specs.title: Usual Effect
specs.html: 'Actual' greater than 'Forecast' is good for currency;

specs.title: Frequency
specs.html: Released monthly, on the first business day after the month ends;

specs.title: Next Release
specs.html: Nov 1, 2024

specs.title: FF Notes
specs.html: Above 50.0 indicates industry expansion, below indicates contraction. The 'Previous' listed is the 'Actual' from the Flash release and therefore the 'History' data will appear unconnected. There are 2 versions of this report released about a week apart – Flash and Final.  The Flash release, which the source first reported in May 2014, is the earliest and thus tends to have the most impact;

specs.title:
Why Traders
Care
specs.html: It's a leading indicator of economic health - businesses react quickly to market conditions, and their purchasing managers hold perhaps the most current and relevant insight into the company's view of the economy;

specs.title: Derived Via
specs.html: Survey of about 400 purchasing managers which asks respondents to rate the relative level of business conditions including employment, production, new orders, prices, supplier deliveries, and inventories;

specs.title: Also Called
specs.html: Jibun Bank Manufacturing PMI;
